TY  - JOUR
T1  - Competitive Procurement Under Demand Uncertainty
AU  - Nti, Kofi O.
Y1  - 1987/11/01
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.33.11.1489
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.33.11.1489
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1489
EP  - 1500
VL  - 33
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Stockpilers of commodities in short supply must frequently contend with game-theoretic ramifications arising from the fact that unit purchasing cost increases with aggregate requirements. In this paper, a competitive inventory procurement model for countries facing uncertain demand is analyzed as a game of strategy. Noncooperative and cooperative aspects of the problem are examined. There are significant incentives for cooperating. Some implications of this analysis for strategic petroleum stockpiling models are discussed.
AB  - Stockpilers of commodities in short supply must frequently contend with game-theoretic ramifications arising from the fact that unit purchasing cost increases with aggregate requirements. In this paper, a competitive inventory procurement model for countries facing uncertain demand is analyzed as a game of strategy. Noncooperative and cooperative aspects of the problem are examined. There are significant incentives for cooperating. Some implications of this analysis for strategic petroleum stockpiling models are discussed.
